[src:apache-thrift/apache-thrift] It uses a remote procedure call (RPC) framework and combines a software stack with a code generation engine to build cross-platform services.
[src:apache-thrift/apache-thrift] Thrift can connect applications written in a variety of languages and frameworks, including ActionScript, C, C++, C#, Cocoa, Delphi, Erlang, Go, Haskell, Java, JavaScript, Objective-C, OCaml, Perl, PHP, Python, Ruby, Elixir, Rust, Scala, Smalltalk, and Swift.
[src:apache-thrift/apache-thrift] The implementation was described in an April 2007 technical paper released by Facebook, now hosted on Apache.
[src:apache-thrift/apache-thrift] Thrift includes a complete stack for creating clients and servers.
[src:apache-thrift/apache-thrift] The top part is generated code from the Thrift definition.
[src:apache-thrift/apache-thrift] From this file, the services generate client and processor codes.
[src:apache-thrift/apache-thrift] In contrast to built-in types, created data structures are sent as a result of generated code.
[src:apache-thrift/apache-thrift] The protocol and transport layer are part of the runtime library.
[src:apache-thrift/apache-thrift] With Thrift, it is possible to define a service and change the protocol and transport without recompiling the code.
[src:apache-thrift/apache-thrift] Besides the client part, Thrift includes server infrastructure such as blocking, non-blocking, and multi-threaded servers.
[src:apache-thrift/apache-thrift] The underlying I/O part of the stack is implemented differently for different programming languages.
[src:apache-thrift/apache-thrift] Thrift is written in C++, but can create code for some other programming languages.
[src:apache-thrift/apache-thrift] To create a Thrift service, one has to write Thrift files that describe it, generate the code in the destination language, write some code to start the server, and call it from the client.
[src:apache-thrift/apache-thrift] Thrift will generate the code out of this descriptive information.
[src:apache-thrift/apache-thrift] For instance, in Java, the `PhoneType` will be `enum` inside the `Phone` class.
[src:apache-thrift/interface-description-language] An **interface description language** or **interface definition language** (**IDL**) is a generic term for a language that lets a program or object written in one language communicate with another program written in an unknown language.
[src:apache-thrift/interface-description-language] IDLs are usually used to describe data types and interfaces in a language-independent way, for example, between those written in C++ and those written in Java.
[src:apache-thrift/interface-description-language] IDLs are commonly used in remote procedure call software.
[src:apache-thrift/interface-description-language] In these cases the machines at either end of the *link* may be using different operating systems and computer languages.
[src:apache-thrift/interface-description-language] IDLs offer a bridge between the two different systems.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] In computer science, **marshalling** or **marshaling** (US spelling) is the process of transforming the memory representation of an object into a data format suitable for storage or transmission, especially between different runtimes.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] It is typically used when data must be moved between different parts of a computer program or from one program to another.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling simplifies complex communications, because it allows using *composite objects* instead of being restricted to *primitive objects*.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling is sometimes used as synonymous with serializing, while serialization is actually one step in the process of marshalling an object.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling and serialization might thus be done differently, although some form of serialization is usually used to do marshalling.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] The term *deserialization* is somewhat similar to *un*-marshalling a dry object "on the server side", i.e., demarshalling (or unmarshalling) to get a live object back: the serialized object is transformed into an internal data structure, i.e., a live object within the target runtime.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] It usually corresponds to the exact inverse process of marshalling, although sometimes both ends of the process trigger specific business logic.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] The accurate definition of marshalling differs across programming languages such as Python, Java, and .NET, and in some contexts, is used interchangeably with serialization.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] To "serialize" an object means to convert its state into a byte stream in such a way that the byte stream may be converted back into a copy of the object, which is unmarshalling in essence.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] Different programming languages either make or don’t make the distinction between the two concepts.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] In the Java-related RFC 2713, marshalling is used when serializing objects for remote invocation.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] An object that is marshalled records the state of the original object and it contains the codebase (*codebase* here refers to a list of URLs where the object code can be loaded from, and not source code).
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] Hence, in order to convert the object state and codebase(s), unmarshalling must be done.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshaller interface automatically converts the marshalled data containing codebase(s) into an executable Java object in JAXB.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] Any object that can be deserialized can be unmarshalled.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling is used within implementations of different remote procedure call (RPC) mechanisms, where it is necessary to transport data between processes and/or between threads.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] In Microsoft's Component Object Model (COM), interface pointers must be marshalled when crossing COM apartment boundaries.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] In the .NET Framework, the conversion between an unmanaged type and a CLR type, as in the P/Invoke process, is also an example of an action that requires marshalling to take place.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] Additionally, marshalling is used extensively within scripts and applications that use the XPCOM technologies provided within the Mozilla application framework.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] The Mozilla Firefox browser is a popular application built with this framework, that additionally allows scripting languages to use XPCOM through XPConnect (Cross-Platform Connect).
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] In the Microsoft Windows family of operating systems the entire set of device drivers for Direct3D are kernel-mode drivers.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] The user-mode portion of the API is handled by the DirectX runtime provided by Microsoft.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] This is an issue because calling kernel-mode operations from user-mode requires performing a system call, and this inevitably forces the CPU to switch to "kernel mode".
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] This is a slow operation, taking on the order of microseconds to complete.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] During this time, the CPU is unable to perform any operations.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] As such, minimizing the number of times this switching operation must be performed would optimize performance to a substantive degree.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] Linux OpenGL drivers are split in two: a kernel-driver and a user-space driver.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] The user-space driver does all the translation of OpenGL commands into machine code to be submitted to the GPU.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] To reduce the number of system calls, the user-space driver implements marshalling.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] If the GPU's command buffer is full of rendering data, the API could simply store the requested rendering call in a temporary buffer and, when the command buffer is close to being empty, it can perform a switch to kernel-mode and add a number of stored commands all at once.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] Marshalling data requires some kind of data transfer, which leverages a specific data format to be chosen as the serialization target.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] XML is one such format and means of transferring data between systems.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] Microsoft, for example, uses it as the basis of the file formats of the various components (Word, Excel, Access, PowerPoint, etc.) of the Microsoft Office suite (see Office Open XML).
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] While this typically results in a verbose wire format, XML's fully-bracketed "start-tag", "end-tag" syntax allows provision of more accurate diagnostics and easier recovery from transmission or disk errors.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] In addition, because the tags occur repeatedly, one can use standard compression methods to shrink the content—all the Office file formats are created by zipping the raw XML.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] Alternative formats such as JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) are more concise, but correspondingly less robust for error recovery.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] Once the data is transferred to a program or an application, it needs to be converted back to an object for usage.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] Hence, unmarshalling is generally used in the receiver end of the implementations of Remote Method Invocation (RMI) and Remote procedure call (RPC) mechanisms to unmarshal transmitted objects in an executable form.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] JAXB or Java Architecture for XML Binding is the most common framework used by developers to marshal and unmarshal Java objects.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] JAXB provides for the interconversion between fundamental data types supported by Java and standard XML schema data types.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] `System.Xml.Serialization.XmlSerializer` is the framework used by C# developers to marshal and unmarshal C# objects.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] One of the advantages of C# over Java is that C# natively supports marshalling due to the inclusion of `System.Xml.Serialization.XmlSerializer` class.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] Java, on the other hand requires a non-native glue code in the form of JAXB to support marshalling.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] An example of unmarshalling is the conversion of an XML representation of an object to the default representation of the object in any programming language.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] Unmarshalling is the process of converting the XML representation to the default executable Java representation, and running that very code to get a consistent, live object back.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] Had a different format been chosen, the unmarshalling process would have been different, but the end result in the target runtime would be the same.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] The process of unmarshalling XML data into an executable Java object is taken care of by the in-built `jakarta.xml.bind.Unmarshaller` (formally `javax.xml.bind.Unmarshaller`) class.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshal methods defined in the `jakarta.xml.bind.Unmarshaller` class are overloaded to accept XML from different types of input such as a `java.io.File`, `java.io.FileInputStream`, or `java.net.URL`.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] Unmarshal methods can deserialize an entire XML document or a small part of it.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] When the XML root element is globally declared, these methods utilize the `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBContext`'s mapping of XML root elements to JAXB mapped classes to initiate the unmarshalling.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] If the mappings are not sufficient and the root elements are declared locally, the unmarshal methods use `declaredType` methods for the unmarshalling process.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] These two approaches can be understood below.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshal method uses `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBContext` (formerly `javax.xml.bind.JAXBContext`) to unmarshal the XML data, when the root element is globally declared.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] The `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBContext` object always maintains a mapping of the globally declared XML element and its name to a JAXB mapped class.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] If the XML element name or its `@xsi:type` attribute matches the JAXB mapped class, the unmarshal method transforms the XML data using the appropriate JAXB mapped class.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] However, if the XML element name has no match, the unmarshal process will abort and throw an `jakarta.xml.bind.UnmarshalException` (formerly `javax.xml.bind.UnmarshalException`).
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] This can be avoided by using the unmarshal by `declaredType` methods.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] When the root element is not declared globally, the application assists the unmarshaller by application-provided mapping using `declaredType` parameters.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] By an order of precedence, even if the root name has a mapping to an appropriate JAXB class, the `declaredType` overrides the mapping.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] However, if the `@xsi:type` attribute of the XML data has a mapping to an appropriate JAXB class, then this takes precedence over declaredType parameter.
[src:apache-thrift/marshalling-computer-science] The unmarshal methods by `declaredType` parameters always return a `jakarta.xml.bind.JAXBElement<T>` instance.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] That is, the programmer writes essentially the same code whether the subroutine is local to the executing program, or remote.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] This is a form of server interaction (caller is client, executor is server), typically implemented via a request–response message passing system.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] In the object-oriented programming paradigm, RPCs are represented by remote method invocation (RMI).
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] The RPC model implies a level of location transparency, namely that calling procedures are largely the same whether they are local or remote, but usually, they are not identical, so local calls can be distinguished from remote calls.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] Remote calls are usually orders of magnitude slower and less reliable than local calls, so distinguishing them is important.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] Many different (often incompatible) technologies have been used to implement the concept.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] Request–response protocols date to early distributed computing in the late 1960s, theoretical proposals of remote procedure calls as the model of network operations date to the 1970s, and practical implementations date to the early 1980s.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] Bruce Jay Nelson is generally credited with coining the term "remote procedure call" in 1981.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] Remote procedure calls used in modern operating systems trace their roots back to the RC 4000 multiprogramming system, which used a request-response communication protocol for process synchronization.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] The idea of treating network operations as remote procedure calls goes back at least to the 1970s in early ARPANET documents.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] In 1978, Per Brinch Hansen proposed Distributed Processes, a language for distributed computing based on "external requests" consisting of procedure calls between processes.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] One of the earliest practical implementations was in 1982 by Brian Randell and colleagues for their Newcastle Connection between UNIX machines.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] This was soon followed by "Lupine" by Andrew Birrell and Bruce Nelson in the Cedar environment at Xerox PARC.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] Lupine automatically generated stubs, providing type-safe bindings, and used an efficient protocol for communication.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] One of the first business uses of RPC was by Xerox under the name "Courier" in 1981.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] The first popular implementation of RPC on Unix was Sun's RPC (now called ONC RPC), used as the basis for Network File System (NFS).
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] In the 1990s, with the popularity of object-oriented programming, an alternative model of remote method invocation (RMI) was widely implemented, such as in Common Object Request Broker Architecture (CORBA, 1991) and Java remote method invocation.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] RMIs, in turn, fell in popularity with the rise of the internet, particularly in the 2000s.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] An RPC is initiated by the *client*, which sends a request message to a known remote *server* to execute a specified procedure with supplied parameters.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] The remote server sends a response to the client, and the application continues its process.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] While the server is processing the call, the client is blocked (it waits until the server has finished processing before resuming execution), unless the client sends an asynchronous request to the server, such as an XMLHttpRequest.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] There are many variations and subtleties in various implementations, resulting in a variety of different (incompatible) RPC protocols.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] An important difference between remote procedure calls and local calls is that remote calls can fail because of unpredictable network problems.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] Also, callers generally must deal with such failures without knowing whether the remote procedure was actually invoked.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] Idempotent procedures (those that have no additional effects if called more than once) are easily handled, but enough difficulties remain that code to call remote procedures is often confined to carefully written low-level subsystems.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] The client stub packs the parameters into a message and makes a system call to send the message.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] Packing the parameters is called marshalling.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] The client's local operating system sends the message from the client machine to the server machine.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] The local operating system on the server machine passes the incoming packets to the server stub.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] The server stub unpacks the parameters from the message.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] Unpacking the parameters is called unmarshalling.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] Finally, the server stub calls the server procedure.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] The reply traces the same steps in the reverse direction.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] To let different clients access servers, a number of standardized RPC systems have been created.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] Most of these use an interface description language (IDL) to let various platforms call the RPC.
[src:apache-thrift/remote-procedure-call] The IDL files can then be used to generate code to interface between the client and servers.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] In distributed computing, a **stub** is a program that acts as a temporary replacement for a remote service or object.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] It allows the client application to access a service as if it were local, while hiding the details of the underlying network communication.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] This can simplify the development process, as the client application does not need to be aware of the complexities of distributed computing.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] Instead, it can rely on the stub to handle the remote communication, while providing a familiar interface for the developer to work with.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] The stub represents a remote object or service on a local system.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] It acts as a proxy for the remote service and allows the client program to make method calls on the remote object as if it were local.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] In modern microservices architectures, stubs can also be used for service virtualization—allowing developers to test interactions between components without requiring the actual remote service to be running.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] The process of generating stubs involves creating a client-side proxy object that provides the same interface as the remote service, but routes method calls to the actual remote object.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] In distributed computing, a stub is a piece of code that converts parameters passed between the client and server during a remote procedure call (RPC).
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] The main purpose of an RPC is to allow a local computer (client) to invoke procedures on a remote computer (server).
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] Since the client and server have different address spaces, the parameters used in a function call must be converted.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] Otherwise, the parameter values would be unusable because pointers to parameters in one computer's memory would reference different data on the other computer.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] Also, the client and server can have different data representations, even for simple parameters like integers (e.g., big-endian versus little-endian).
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] Stubs handle parameter conversion, making a remote procedure call look like a local function call to the remote computer.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] Stub libraries are crucial in distributed computing, as they allow for local procedure calls to be made to remote objects or services.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] The client-side stub or proxy is responsible for converting the parameters used in a function call and deconverting the results returned by the server after executing the function, a process known as marshalling.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] The stub libraries must be installed on both the client and server, with the server-side stub, or server skeleton, being responsible for deconverting the parameters passed by the client and converting the results after executing the function.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] In classical RPC systems, the client uses a **client-side stub** (proxy) which packages the parameters of a call (*marshalling*) and sends them over the network.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] On the server side, a **server-side stub** (skeleton) unpacks the request (*unmarshalling*), invokes the procedure, and then sends the result back.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] This mechanism allows the client to call remote functions as if they were local.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] Many RPC implementations use an **Interface Definition Language (IDL)** to describe services.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] The IDL compiler automatically generates both client and server stubs, including all necessary marshalling and unmarshalling operations.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] In **gRPC**, the client holds a local object called a **stub**, which implements the same methods as the remote service.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] When a method is invoked, the stub serializes the request into Protobuf, sends it to the server, and returns the structured response, making remote calls transparent to the client.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] In **Java Remote Method Invocation (RMI)**, stub classes are generated using the `rmic` compiler.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] The client interacts with these stub classes to invoke methods on remote objects as if they were local, while the underlying stub manages the network communication.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] In distributed object communication (such as CORBA), stubs act as proxies for clients while server skeletons handle incoming requests.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] They are responsible for network communication, parameter marshalling, and method invocation.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] Set up the test environment by initializing the component under test and its stubs.
[src:apache-thrift/stub-distributed-computing] It's crucial to use stubs only when needed, as they may introduce additional complexity and maintenance overhead.
[src:apache-thrift/wire-protocol] In computer networking, a **wire protocol** refers to a way of getting data from point to point: A wire protocol is needed if more than one application has to interoperate.
[src:apache-thrift/wire-protocol] It generally refers to communication protocols higher than the physical layer.
[src:apache-thrift/wire-protocol] In contrast to transport protocols at the transport level (like TCP or UDP), the term *wire protocol* is used to describe a common way to exchange information at the application level.
[src:apache-thrift/wire-protocol] It refers to an application layer protocol and defines all the required attributes for the data exchange, like data types (units of data, message formats, etc.), communication endpoints and capabilities (such as delivery guarantees, direction of communication, etc.).
[src:apache-thrift/wire-protocol] Usually, the data is represented at the application level as a common infoset (e.g.
[src:apache-thrift/wire-protocol] XML, JSON, YAML) and requires a mechanism of data binding (using e.g. a common encoding scheme like XSD).
[src:apache-thrift/wire-protocol] The wire protocol may be either text-based or a binary protocol.
[src:apache-thrift/wire-protocol] Although an important architectural decision, this is a separate matter from the distinction between wire protocols and programmatic APIs.
[src:apache-thrift/wire-protocol] In electronics, a wire protocol is the mechanism used to transmit data from one point to another.
[src:apache-thrift/wire-protocol] A wire protocol provides the means for the interoperation of one or more applications in a network.
[src:apache-thrift/wire-protocol] They often refer to distributed object protocols, or they use applications that were designed to work together.
[src:apache-thrift/wire-protocol] As the name suggests, these distributed object protocols run in different processes in one or several computers that are connected over a network.
[src:apache-thrift/wire-protocol] Wire protocols provide the means for a program running under one operating system to communicate with a program running under some other operating system over a network such as an organization's intranet or the Internet.
[src:apache-thrift/wire-protocol] The protocol thus interconnects multiple platforms.
[src:apache-thrift/wire-protocol] Some wire protocols are language-independent, allowing the communication of programs written in different programming languages.
